I wanted to express some thoughts I have generally from my observations around life. There's a lot of them. 

# The art of war
War should be quick. 

# People change, you only have yourself
I have had a lot of friends over the years and our relationships have changed drastically. It's similar to companies dominating the stock market. For some time it was Apple and then it was Nvidia. And before all of that maybe it was IBM. But companies change over time and so do people.

People are shaped by influence around them. The three ways that people would change after turning 22 are:
1. Trauma. Something traumatic happens to you and now you perceive differently. This trauma can come in a lot of ways. Betrayal, disaster, etc.
2. Religion. You have belief in something then you'll change your life to fit it because that becomes the definition to how you live it.
3. Significant other. I think that these people may influence you over time and it can vary per person. 

Be careful about who you choose to be close with. 

You may confide in someone with all your secrets and thoughts. But that confidement can be used against you the moment you get on that person's other side.

# The world is not as it seems
Everything is by design. 

Looking at root fundamentals, what we see and hear.

For every person you observe, its like going to a restaurant. 

What you see is an environment in the various shapes it can be from the tables to chairs to cups and lighting. 
A server with a behavior nice or rude or somewhere in between. 
Some food that looks or tastes good or bad, from the plating to the freshness to the light that affects it. 

But what you see, as you're sitting down at the restaurant, might not be what you see behind the closed doors. 

Maybe behind those doors, they cook everything fresh, have a sanitary kitchen, have a love for the game and put care into cheffing.
Or maybe they spit in your food, do something illegal like money laundering, have a dirty kitchen, prepare everything ahead of time.

You really don't know unless you know and thats how I feel like the state of the world and what goes on largely follows. 

News is by design and controlled by certain people.
Social media are also designed and controlled by certain people.
And the same thing can be said for nations. There's an illusion that we are in control but we really aren't.

The same thing can be said about your iPhone or Android. The only way you can have full control is through jail breakage or if you hold the keys to the secrets.

It's the most innocently appearing that are the most guilty.

## Professionalism
Another thing that I see is that we create these artificial barriers to make things feel less awkward. Because people naturally feel uncomfortable when they experience something new.

I think thats what we did with religion and law as well.  

Successful people result from some thing out of the ordinary, as the general person is within the ordinary. 

We are trained to follow the same paths and become comfortable with them so thats whats shaped society and for us to be the way we are as communities and people.

# Absence is bliss
I think that maintaining relationships with people is a combination of closeness and absence. You want to be really close, and you also may need to be absent as it is .

# Wrong things aren't wrong
Not to get philosophical but I feel like the fine line between 'good' and 'bad' is based on subjective vibes. What you'd get a death penalty in Singapore is different from what you would in the US or in Sudan. 

I also feel like people are generally opinionated. 

The only thing that matters is what YOU want. 

Wrong and right will always be subjective and don't let someone make you think that you're right or wrong. Of course there are certain people or actions that the majority of people and even the vast majority of people will agree on. But I feel like some of those lead to extremely bad and good things for the world (or both). 

We'll always disagree with each other, so be strong in what you think.  

We use principles like Utilitarianism as guardrails but these principles don't always prevail.  

# Life is not fair
I don't think we'll ever have world peace. There will always be resentment towards the common man.

The reason is because that's just naturally how we are. And if you look at history, there's never been one moment where that's happened. We observe other living organisms and its the same thing. 

It all revolves around power for animals in whatever form it is. For humans that is a few things and I think it becomes more fundamental the 'dumber' an organism gets.

The only exception to this I see is if a) we are able to genetically modify humans to forget or b) if something captures us and constrains us (robot, alien, supernatural, idea, ...)

# The biggest weapon is the one that infiltrates the mind
Humans are subject to emotion and because of it we'll move mountains and create wars.

People are able to do what they do because they know how to infiltrate the mind.

The biggest drivers of human behavior include lust, hunger, comfort, fear, disgust, love, curiosity, justice, status.

These are interconnected, and what we see around us is used to channel these motives in us, and the reason why people choose to channel these motives is since they are bounded by these motives.

People have different levels of volume for their boundance in these different motives. 

# The marionette and the marionettist (the puppet and the puppeteer)
In life we must fight to mitigate being a puppet. We must minimize the strings that are controlling us as a puppet. The ideal is that we become a puppeteer (for ourselves, with the most powerful being of other people.)

The puppeteer needs to be observant and truly know how to control the puppets for the puppet could become self aware like an inanimate object turning animate.

In real life, the puppeteer is the person who has the power over a subject of any kind (persons, places, things,) for it is these subjects that are the puppets.

# Anything is hackable

Despite how robust we make our digital security measures, someone can still hack it.

Despite how robust we design our banks, someone can still steal the money.

Despite how well kept our secrets are, someone can still capture them.

People think of clever ways of doing this, for the direct and obvious approaches are the ones that are guarded heavily against, and the most clever which are the least expected.

I think that this along with everything mentioned earlier can be tested by history. 

# Leave no trace
This is what people do. They leave no trace. They do something terrible and cover it up.

Whether its through scapegoats, money, influence and pressure over others, etc.

This is how things have been done throughout history.

# Ignorance is bliss
What you don't know is what will not serve as an impedence on you mentally.

You can artificially ignore things entirely so that it won't cause a bad effect on you.

For example, not looking the news; not having social media installed; not responding to messages.

These can all be looked at bad but also underratedly good. 

Because by having ignorance, you are more focused on the things you care about. And with more focus, you can get more done.

This is also a double-edged sword. 

Because if you ignore some things then they will bite you back. 

Be selective of what you focus on and intentional on what you ignore. 

# Think from the root / Think in first principles? / A tree grows with nurturing of the roots?
This makes me think of 'everything is by design', because when someone asks a question there is an underlying root that they are asking it for. 

I am staying at a friend's apartment with 8 roommates and was questioned by 1 of them. 

I think that there is an underlying root concern which is why he had questioned why I am staying in their closet in the first place. 

So when I talk to him tonight, I will talk from the root.
